Methods for data preparation¶

In [612]:
def create_dataset(df,look_back):
    """
    perform separation of the data into X (input) and Y (output)
    IMPORTANT: slicing must be performed with iloc, because
    otherwise method will give error

    Args:
        df - dataframe separation of data for which is required
        look_back - how many records to keep in the input set,
                    after which comes one record for output set

    Return:
        tuple of arrays, where one is input set and another
        is output set, both transformed into Numpy arrays
    """
    data_x, data_y = [], []
    for index in range(len(df) - look_back - 1):
        a = df[index:(index+look_back)]
        data_x.append(a)
        data_y.append(df[index+look_back])
    return np.array(data_x), np.array(data_y)
In [613]:
def split_data(x, y, test_size):
    """
    split input and output sets into training and testing one

    Args:
        x - input set
        y - output set
        test_size - size of the test set

    Return:
        4 elements (in the same sequence): input train,
        output train, input test and output test sets of data
    """
    #   position in the dataset, where will be performed
    # separation of dataset into training set and test
    # set
    pos = int(round(len(x) * (1 - test_size)))
    x_train, y_train = x[:pos], y[:pos]
    x_test, y_test = x[pos:], y[pos:]
    return x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test

In [616]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 7))
ax.plot(airline_passengers_df.index, airline_passengers_df["Passengers"], color='b')
ax.set_xlabel("Month nr.")
ax.set_ylabel("Count of passengers")
ax.set_title("Distribution of the passengers from 1949 till 1960")
ax.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.show()

Even visually can be seen that there is a trend to slow increase count of passengers. Another moment is repetative (cyclical) manner of passengers count peaks. While the first aspect can be explained by inreasing number of international flights due to increase of jets/planes with decrease of price for such services (need to check), the second aspect can be explained by seasonality of the flights.

Seasonality means that there are many persons performing international flights during their vacation and therefore, considering that most of the people are taking vacation during Spring and Summer (need to check), distribution of the records will look cyclical with smaller peak around Spring and bigger peak around Summer.

To perform efficient analysis of the data it is required to remove the increasing trend and ensure data stability, after which model training can be performed

Trend removal¶

Actions presented below allowed removal of the trend in data and now there is a problem of varying range of values. To solve this issue can be tried strategy of taking log of the passengers difference and sin of the passengers difference. Therefore, here will be performed comparison of those two approaches to see which one will lead to better results.

In [617]:
airline_passengers_df["Fixed Passengers"] = airline_passengers_df["Passengers"] - airline_passengers_df["Passengers"].shift(1)

Cycle removal¶

Log approach¶

In [618]:
airline_passengers_df["Log Passengers"] = np.log(airline_passengers_df["Passengers"])

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 7))
ax.plot(airline_passengers_df.index, airline_passengers_df["Log Passengers"], color='b')
ax.set_xlabel("Month nr.")
ax.set_ylabel("Count of passengers")
ax.set_title("Distribution of the passengers monthly difference from 1949 till 1960")
ax.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.show()

Here can be seen that log operation performed reduce of the values range and stabilized distribution, but concept of cycles in data remained

In [619]:
airline_passengers_df["Log Diff Passengers"] = airline_passengers_df["Log Passengers"] - airline_passengers_df["Log Passengers"].shift(1)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 7))
ax.plot(airline_passengers_df.index, airline_passengers_df["Log Diff Passengers"], color='b')
ax.set_xlabel("Month nr.")
ax.set_ylabel("Count of passengers")
ax.set_title("Distribution of the passengers monthly difference from 1949 till 1960")
ax.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.show()

Application of the difference on top of the data where log was performed led to removal of the cycles and can be seen that behavior of the data has some similarities to the cyclical one, but much less

Sin approach¶

In [621]:
airline_passengers_df["Sin Passengers"] = np.sin(airline_passengers_df["Passengers"])

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 7))
ax.plot(airline_passengers_df.index, airline_passengers_df["Sin Passengers"], color='b')
ax.set_xlabel("Month nr.")
ax.set_ylabel("Count of passengers")
ax.set_title("Distribution of the passengers monthly difference from 1949 till 1960")
ax.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.show()

Application of the sin hevily changes the distribution to match a range of values between 0 and 1. Another interesting moment is that differentiation will lead to even better distributions, but there is one great problem

Sin function impact the original distribution and heavily changes it. In case of performing reverse operation it is possible to lose original range of values. It is possible to fix it temporarily via application of the MinMax scaler, but considering further possible increase of the passengers count it will be just a temporary solution or will require readaptation of the model to new data

Initial LSTM check (no data changes, only MinMax scaler)¶

The original data can be used for performing predictions using LSTM. Considering that all other models were giving strange results it was decided to perform LSTM model predictions using the original data with MinMax scaling of the records.

All predcitions will be then transformed back to the original form using inverse operation. Another important moment is that compared to the laboratory work solution, where each 10 months where used to predict each 11-th month, here will be used concept of predicting next month value basing on the current one.

In [629]:
# make predictions
train_predict_pure = model.predict(trainX)
test_predict_pure = model.predict(testX)

# invert predictions
trainPredict = scaler.inverse_transform(train_predict_pure)
trainY = scaler.inverse_transform(trainY.reshape(len(trainY), 1))
testPredict = scaler.inverse_transform(test_predict_pure)
testY = scaler.inverse_transform(testY.reshape(len(testY), 1))

# calculate root mean squared error
trainScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(trainY, trainPredict[:,0]))
print('Train Score: %.2f RMSE' % (trainScore))
testScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(testY, testPredict[:,0]))
print('Test Score: %.2f RMSE' % (testScore))

Train Score: 22.78 RMSE
Test Score: 50.63 RMSE

Train and Test scores demonstrate relatively good error of the model. It is important to consider changing passengers count through time with trend of data to go up and up. Therefore, such rate demonstrates acceptable error.

plt.show()

What can be said in result? First of all, performing the LSTM over the original data gives relatively good results and can be seen that deviation of the predictions on the test set are not too far from the real ones and therefore efficiency of the model is relatively high. However, application of any change (new technology in flights, crisis, possible decrease of the ticket price) will lead to the heavy changes in distribution and therefore model will lose its efficiency.

Another problem is that there is a trend in the way how data behaves, meaning that distribution will progress through time and it is possible that model will not be able to "stay in touch" with trend.

To perform data adaptation, removing trend and possibly cycling of data it is possible to perform log operation in pair with differenciation. As one of the assumptions there was also provided sin operation, but there is one great problem with this operation - sin and any another trigonometric operation performs well with values in range from 0 to 1, but considering trend of data and how it distributes through time there will be values going out of the range (even transformed with MinMax scaler) and therefore application of the sin will lead to loss of data and then to errors in performing predictions.

The only option is to perform log difference. Considering that before this all the LSTM related work was performed with several deviations from the laboratory work conditions (for test was taken 1/3 of the dataset and look_back specified with value 1), it is required to demonstrate in the next chapter how will the data look in case of matching laboratory work conditions, but without the data transformations.

In this chapter will be demonstrated work with the original data, without application of any transformations, but with application of the "window" concept, when each 10 months are used to predict value of the 11-th month

In [641]:
plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])

plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'test'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

Compared to the results of previous model this one performs worse and can be seen that there is more interesting case of loss distribution, where loss at some point instead of decreasing goes to rise, demonstrating model overfit.

Next chapter demonstrates the same model, but this time with apploed log difference over the data to remove trend and stabilize distribution. Considering that it is required to make a log and then take a difference it will be required to store the first element of the dataset for further reconstruction of values.

So, the transformation will work like:

  1. Take log of the each record;
  2. Apply the differential over the data;

The backwards transformation will work like:

  1. Reverse the differential, knowing the first element of the original dataset;
  2. Find exponential of the record.

LSTM laboratory work conditions met, log with differential applied¶

In [642]:
data = dataset.values
data = data.astype('float32')
log_data = np.log(data)

log_diff_data = np.diff(log_data, axis=0)
In [643]:
train_size = int(len(log_diff_data) * 0.9167)
test_size = len(log_diff_data) - train_size
train, test = log_diff_data[0:train_size,:], log_diff_data[train_size:len(log_diff_data),:]
print(len(train), len(test))

look_back = 10
trainX, trainY = create_dataset(train, look_back)
testX, testY = create_dataset(test, look_back)

131 12
In [644]:
trainX = np.reshape(trainX, (trainX.shape[0], 1, trainX.shape[1]))
testX = np.reshape(testX, (testX.shape[0], 1, testX.shape[1]))

model = Sequential()
model.add(LSTM(4, input_shape=(1, look_back)))
model.add(Dense(25))
model.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
history = model.fit(trainX, trainY, epochs=100, validation_data=(testX, testY), batch_size=1, verbose=2)

# make predictions
train_predict_pure = model.predict(trainX)
test_predict_pure = model.predict(testX)

Here also can be seen that model is overfitting after some stage without improvement of the result and therefore it will be great to reduce epoches count to around 15-20

In [649]:
data = dataset.values
data = data.astype('float32')
log_data = np.log(data)

first_train_y = log_data[look_back]
# first_test_value = log_data[train_size]

train_predictions = train_predict_pure[:,0]
train_predictions = np.insert(train_predictions, 0, first_train_y)
train_predictions = np.exp(train_predictions.cumsum())

original_train_Y = trainY
original_train_Y = np.insert(original_train_Y, 0, first_train_y)
original_train_Y = np.exp(original_train_Y.cumsum())

trainScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(original_train_Y, train_predictions))
print('Train Score: %.2f RMSE' % (trainScore))

Train Score: 87.93 RMSE

RMSE is relatively acceptable considering values closer to the end of the reviewed time period, but the problems start when looking at the difference between original dataset values and predicted ones

In [650]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.plot(original_train_Y, color='g', label='original train y')
plt.plot(train_predictions, color='r', label='predicted train y')
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel("nr. of month")
plt.ylabel("amount of passengers")
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.show()

While the original data contains trend with tendency to increasing passengers count, predictions behave with very similar shape of distribution, but it is like forced in and therefore there is a big difference between predictions and original data in the middle of taken time window

It is required to check approach if increased number of epoches will lead to better results (but there already is an overfit)

LSTM (500 epoches) laboratory work conditions met, log with differential applied¶

In [651]:
data = dataset.values
data = data.astype('float32')
log_data = np.log(data)

log_diff_data = np.diff(log_data, axis=0)

train_size = int(len(log_diff_data) * 0.9167)
test_size = len(log_diff_data) - train_size
train, test = log_diff_data[0:train_size,:], log_diff_data[train_size:len(log_diff_data),:]
print(len(train), len(test))

look_back = 10
trainX, trainY = create_dataset(train, look_back)
testX, testY = create_dataset(test, look_back)

trainX = np.reshape(trainX, (trainX.shape[0], 1, trainX.shape[1]))
testX = np.reshape(testX, (testX.shape[0], 1, testX.shape[1]))

model = Sequential()
model.add(LSTM(4, input_shape=(1, look_back)))
model.add(Dense(25))
model.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
history = model.fit(trainX, trainY, epochs=500, validation_data=(testX, testY), batch_size=1, verbose=2)

# make predictions
train_predict_pure = model.predict(trainX)
test_predict_pure = model.predict(testX)

In [652]:
# calculate root mean squared error
trainScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(trainY, train_predict_pure[:,0]))
print('Train Score: %.2f RMSE' % (trainScore))
testScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(testY, test_predict_pure[:,0]))
print('Test Score: %.2f RMSE' % (testScore))

train_predict_df = pd.DataFrame(train_predict_pure[:,0])
test_predict_df = pd.DataFrame(test_predict_pure[:,0])
predict_df = pd.concat([train_predict_df, test_predict_df])
predict_df.reset_index(inplace=True)
predict_df.drop(columns=["index"], inplace=True)

# plot baseline and predictions
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.plot(log_diff_data, color='b', label="original data")
plt.plot(predict_df[:len(train_predict_df)].index + 10, predict_df[:len(train_predict_df)][0], color="g",
         label='training predictions')
plt.plot(predict_df[len(train_predict_df):].index, 
         predict_df[len(train_predict_df):][0], color="r", label="testing predictions")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.show()

Train Score: 0.03 RMSE
Test Score: 0.07 RMSE

Model makes great match of predictions to the transformed original data, but it is required to check behavior in the original form of data

data = dataset.values
data = data.astype('float32')
log_data = np.log(data)

first_train_y = log_data[look_back]
# first_test_value = log_data[train_size]

train_predictions = train_predict_pure[:,0]
train_predictions = np.insert(train_predictions, 0, first_train_y)
train_predictions = np.exp(train_predictions.cumsum())

original_train_Y = trainY
original_train_Y = np.insert(original_train_Y, 0, first_train_y)
original_train_Y = np.exp(original_train_Y.cumsum())

trainScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(original_train_Y, train_predictions))
print('Train Score: %.2f RMSE' % (trainScore))

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.plot(original_train_Y, color='g', label='original train y')
plt.plot(train_predictions, color='r', label='predicted train y')
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel("nr. of month")
plt.ylabel("amount of passengers")
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.show()

Train Score: 84.92 RMSE

In this case model achieves almost the same RMSE, but distribution differs from one received in the last model. Here predictions are above original values, but overall shape is still almost identical. And overfit of the model considering lossses is heavy.

Increasing number of the epoches has not given any good result and therefore it will be great to check inreasing number of layers for model and experiment with number of neurons per layer.

LSTM two layers, 50 neurons, 100 epoches, log with differential applied¶

In [655]:
data = dataset.values
data = data.astype('float32')
log_data = np.log(data)

log_diff_data = np.diff(log_data, axis=0)

train_size = int(len(log_diff_data) * 0.9167)
test_size = len(log_diff_data) - train_size
train, test = log_diff_data[0:train_size,:], log_diff_data[train_size:len(log_diff_data),:]
print(len(train), len(test))

look_back = 10
trainX, trainY = create_dataset(train, look_back)
testX, testY = create_dataset(test, look_back)

trainX = np.reshape(trainX, (trainX.shape[0], 1, trainX.shape[1]))
testX = np.reshape(testX, (testX.shape[0], 1, testX.shape[1]))

model = Sequential()
# model.add(LSTM(4, input_shape=(1, look_back)))
model.add(LSTM(4, batch_input_shape=(1, 1, look_back), stateful=True, return_sequences=True))
model.add(Dense(50))
model.add(LSTM(4, batch_input_shape=(1, 1, look_back), stateful=True))
model.add(Dense(50))
model.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
history = model.fit(trainX, trainY, epochs=100, validation_data=(testX, testY), batch_size=1, verbose=2)

# make predictions
train_predict_pure = model.predict(trainX, batch_size=1)
test_predict_pure = model.predict(testX, batch_size=1)

# calculate root mean squared error
trainScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(trainY, train_predict_pure[:, 0]))
print('Train Score: %.2f RMSE' % (trainScore))
testScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(testY, test_predict_pure[:, 0]))
print('Test Score: %.2f RMSE' % (testScore))

train_predict_df = pd.DataFrame(train_predict_pure[:,0])
test_predict_df = pd.DataFrame(test_predict_pure[:,0])
predict_df = pd.concat([train_predict_df, test_predict_df])
predict_df.reset_index(inplace=True)
predict_df.drop(columns=["index"], inplace=True)

# plot baseline and predictions
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.plot(log_diff_data, color='b', label="original data")
plt.plot(predict_df[:len(train_predict_df)].index + 10, predict_df[:len(train_predict_df)][0], color="g",
         label='training predictions')
plt.plot(predict_df[len(train_predict_df):].index, 
         predict_df[len(train_predict_df):][0], color="r", label="testing predictions")
plt.legend() 
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.show()

Train Score: 0.04 RMSE
Test Score: 0.10 RMSE

data = dataset.values
data = data.astype('float32')
log_data = np.log(data)

first_train_y = log_data[look_back]
# first_test_value = log_data[train_size]

train_predictions = train_predict_pure[:,0]
train_predictions = np.insert(train_predictions, 0, first_train_y)
train_predictions = np.exp(train_predictions.cumsum())

original_train_Y = trainY
original_train_Y = np.insert(original_train_Y, 0, first_train_y)
original_train_Y = np.exp(original_train_Y.cumsum())

trainScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(original_train_Y, train_predictions))
print('Train Score: %.2f RMSE' % (trainScore))

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.plot(original_train_Y, color='g', label='original train y')
plt.plot(train_predictions, color='r', label='predicted train y')
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel("nr. of month")
plt.ylabel("amount of passengers")
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.show()

Train Score: 74.48 RMSE

This model contains the best RMSE identifier and distribution looks extremely similar most of the time, but closer to the end predictions start to be much higher than original ones. There is also a heavy overfit (possible number is around 10 epoches)

LSTM two layers, 100 neurons, 100 epoches, log with differential applied¶

In [659]:
data = dataset.values
data = data.astype('float32')
log_data = np.log(data)

log_diff_data = np.diff(log_data, axis=0)

train_size = int(len(log_diff_data) * 0.9167)
test_size = len(log_diff_data) - train_size
train, test = log_diff_data[0:train_size,:], log_diff_data[train_size:len(log_diff_data),:]
print(len(train), len(test))

look_back = 10
trainX, trainY = create_dataset(train, look_back)
testX, testY = create_dataset(test, look_back)

trainX = np.reshape(trainX, (trainX.shape[0], 1, trainX.shape[1]))
testX = np.reshape(testX, (testX.shape[0], 1, testX.shape[1]))

model = Sequential()
# model.add(LSTM(4, input_shape=(1, look_back)))
model.add(LSTM(4, batch_input_shape=(1, 1, look_back), stateful=True, return_sequences=True))
model.add(Dense(100))
model.add(LSTM(4, batch_input_shape=(1, 1, look_back), stateful=True))
model.add(Dense(100))
model.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
history = model.fit(trainX, trainY, epochs=100, validation_data=(testX, testY), batch_size=1, verbose=2)

# make predictions
train_predict_pure = model.predict(trainX, batch_size=1)
test_predict_pure = model.predict(testX, batch_size=1)

# calculate root mean squared error
trainScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(trainY, train_predict_pure[:, 0]))
print('Train Score: %.2f RMSE' % (trainScore))
testScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(testY, test_predict_pure[:, 0]))
print('Test Score: %.2f RMSE' % (testScore))

train_predict_df = pd.DataFrame(train_predict_pure[:,0])
test_predict_df = pd.DataFrame(test_predict_pure[:,0])
predict_df = pd.concat([train_predict_df, test_predict_df])
predict_df.reset_index(inplace=True)
predict_df.drop(columns=["index"], inplace=True)

# plot baseline and predictions
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.plot(log_diff_data, color='b', label="original data")
plt.plot(predict_df[:len(train_predict_df)].index + 10, predict_df[:len(train_predict_df)][0], color="g",
         label='training predictions')
plt.plot(predict_df[len(train_predict_df):].index, 
         predict_df[len(train_predict_df):][0], color="r", label="testing predictions")
plt.legend() 
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.show()

train_predictions = np.insert(train_predictions, 0, first_train_y)
train_predictions = np.exp(train_predictions.cumsum())

original_train_Y = trainY
original_train_Y = np.insert(original_train_Y, 0, first_train_y)
original_train_Y = np.exp(original_train_Y.cumsum())

trainScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(original_train_Y, train_predictions))
print('Train Score: %.2f RMSE' % (trainScore))

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.plot(original_train_Y, color='g', label='original train y')
plt.plot(train_predictions, color='r', label='predicted train y')
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel("nr. of month")
plt.ylabel("amount of passengers")
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')

LSTM three layers, 50 neurons, 100 epoches, log with differential applied¶

In [663]:
data = dataset.values
data = data.astype('float32')
log_data = np.log(data)

log_diff_data = np.diff(log_data, axis=0)

train_size = int(len(log_diff_data) * 0.9167)
test_size = len(log_diff_data) - train_size
train, test = log_diff_data[0:train_size,:], log_diff_data[train_size:len(log_diff_data),:]
print(len(train), len(test))

look_back = 10
trainX, trainY = create_dataset(train, look_back)
testX, testY = create_dataset(test, look_back)

trainX = np.reshape(trainX, (trainX.shape[0], 1, trainX.shape[1]))
testX = np.reshape(testX, (testX.shape[0], 1, testX.shape[1]))

model = Sequential()
# model.add(LSTM(4, input_shape=(1, look_back)))
model.add(LSTM(4, batch_input_shape=(1, 1, look_back), stateful=True, return_sequences=True))
model.add(Dense(50))
model.add(LSTM(4, batch_input_shape=(1, 1, look_back), stateful=True, return_sequences=True))
model.add(Dense(50))
model.add(LSTM(4, batch_input_shape=(1, 1, look_back), stateful=True))
model.add(Dense(50))
model.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
history = model.fit(trainX, trainY, epochs=100, validation_data=(testX, testY), batch_size=1, verbose=2)

# make predictions
train_predict_pure = model.predict(trainX, batch_size=1)
test_predict_pure = model.predict(testX, batch_size=1)

# calculate root mean squared error
trainScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(trainY, train_predict_pure[:, 0]))
print('Train Score: %.2f RMSE' % (trainScore))
testScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(testY, test_predict_pure[:, 0]))
print('Test Score: %.2f RMSE' % (testScore))

train_predict_df = pd.DataFrame(train_predict_pure[:,0])
test_predict_df = pd.DataFrame(test_predict_pure[:,0])
predict_df = pd.concat([train_predict_df, test_predict_df])
predict_df.reset_index(inplace=True)
predict_df.drop(columns=["index"], inplace=True)

# plot baseline and predictions
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.plot(log_diff_data, color='b', label="original data")
plt.plot(predict_df[:len(train_predict_df)].index + 10, predict_df[:len(train_predict_df)][0], color="g",
         label='training predictions')
plt.plot(predict_df[len(train_predict_df):].index, 
         predict_df[len(train_predict_df):][0], color="r", label="testing predictions")
plt.legend() 
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.show()

Train Score: 0.05 RMSE
Test Score: 0.10 RMSE

data = dataset.values
data = data.astype('float32')
log_data = np.log(data)

first_train_y = log_data[look_back]
# first_test_value = log_data[train_size]

train_predictions = train_predict_pure[:,0]
train_predictions = np.insert(train_predictions, 0, first_train_y)
train_predictions = np.exp(train_predictions.cumsum())

original_train_Y = trainY
original_train_Y = np.insert(original_train_Y, 0, first_train_y)
original_train_Y = np.exp(original_train_Y.cumsum())

trainScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(original_train_Y, train_predictions))
print('Train Score: %.2f RMSE' % (trainScore))

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.plot(original_train_Y, color='g', label='original train y')
plt.plot(train_predictions, color='r', label='predicted train y')
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel("nr. of month")
plt.ylabel("amount of passengers")
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.show()

LSTM three layers, 100 neurons, 100 epoches, log with differential applied¶

In [667]:
data = dataset.values
data = data.astype('float32')
log_data = np.log(data)

log_diff_data = np.diff(log_data, axis=0)

train_size = int(len(log_diff_data) * 0.9167)
test_size = len(log_diff_data) - train_size
train, test = log_diff_data[0:train_size,:], log_diff_data[train_size:len(log_diff_data),:]
print(len(train), len(test))

look_back = 10
trainX, trainY = create_dataset(train, look_back)
testX, testY = create_dataset(test, look_back)

trainX = np.reshape(trainX, (trainX.shape[0], 1, trainX.shape[1]))
testX = np.reshape(testX, (testX.shape[0], 1, testX.shape[1]))

model = Sequential()
# model.add(LSTM(4, input_shape=(1, look_back)))
model.add(LSTM(4, batch_input_shape=(1, 1, look_back), stateful=True, return_sequences=True))
model.add(Dense(100))
model.add(LSTM(4, batch_input_shape=(1, 1, look_back), stateful=True, return_sequences=True))
model.add(Dense(100))
model.add(LSTM(4, batch_input_shape=(1, 1, look_back), stateful=True))
model.add(Dense(100))
model.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
history = model.fit(trainX, trainY, epochs=100, validation_data=(testX, testY), batch_size=1, verbose=2)

# make predictions
train_predict_pure = model.predict(trainX, batch_size=1)
test_predict_pure = model.predict(testX, batch_size=1)

# calculate root mean squared error
trainScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(trainY, train_predict_pure[:, 0]))
print('Train Score: %.2f RMSE' % (trainScore))
testScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(testY, test_predict_pure[:, 0]))
print('Test Score: %.2f RMSE' % (testScore))

train_predict_df = pd.DataFrame(train_predict_pure[:,0])
test_predict_df = pd.DataFrame(test_predict_pure[:,0])
predict_df = pd.concat([train_predict_df, test_predict_df])
predict_df.reset_index(inplace=True)
predict_df.drop(columns=["index"], inplace=True)

# plot baseline and predictions
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.plot(log_diff_data, color='b', label="original data")
plt.plot(predict_df[:len(train_predict_df)].index + 10, predict_df[:len(train_predict_df)][0], color="g",
         label='training predictions')
plt.plot(predict_df[len(train_predict_df):].index, 
         predict_df[len(train_predict_df):][0], color="r", label="testing predictions")
plt.legend() 
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.show()

data = dataset.values
data = data.astype('float32')
log_data = np.log(data)

# first_test_value = log_data[train_size]

train_predictions = np.insert(train_predictions, 0, first_train_y)
train_predictions = np.exp(train_predictions.cumsum())

original_train_Y = trainY
original_train_Y = np.insert(original_train_Y, 0, first_train_y)
original_train_Y = np.exp(original_train_Y.cumsum())

trainScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(original_train_Y, train_predictions))
print('Train Score: %.2f RMSE' % (trainScore))

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.plot(original_train_Y, color='g', label='original train y')
plt.plot(train_predictions, color='r', label='predicted train y')
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel("nr. of month")
plt.ylabel("amount of passengers")
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')

LSTM four layers, 50 neurons, 100 epoches, log with differential applied¶

In [671]:
data = dataset.values
data = data.astype('float32')
log_data = np.log(data)

log_diff_data = np.diff(log_data, axis=0)

train_size = int(len(log_diff_data) * 0.9167)
test_size = len(log_diff_data) - train_size
train, test = log_diff_data[0:train_size,:], log_diff_data[train_size:len(log_diff_data),:]
print(len(train), len(test))

look_back = 10
trainX, trainY = create_dataset(train, look_back)
testX, testY = create_dataset(test, look_back)

trainX = np.reshape(trainX, (trainX.shape[0], 1, trainX.shape[1]))
testX = np.reshape(testX, (testX.shape[0], 1, testX.shape[1]))

model = Sequential()
# model.add(LSTM(4, input_shape=(1, look_back)))
model.add(LSTM(4, batch_input_shape=(1, 1, look_back), stateful=True, return_sequences=True))
model.add(Dense(50))
model.add(LSTM(4, batch_input_shape=(1, 1, look_back), stateful=True, return_sequences=True))
model.add(Dense(50))
model.add(LSTM(4, batch_input_shape=(1, 1, look_back), stateful=True, return_sequences=True))
model.add(Dense(50))
model.add(LSTM(4, batch_input_shape=(1, 1, look_back), stateful=True))
model.add(Dense(50))
model.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
history = model.fit(trainX, trainY, epochs=100, validation_data=(testX, testY), batch_size=1, verbose=2)

# make predictions
train_predict_pure = model.predict(trainX, batch_size=1)
test_predict_pure = model.predict(testX, batch_size=1)

# calculate root mean squared error
trainScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(trainY, train_predict_pure[:, 0]))
print('Train Score: %.2f RMSE' % (trainScore))
testScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(testY, test_predict_pure[:, 0]))
print('Test Score: %.2f RMSE' % (testScore))

train_predict_df = pd.DataFrame(train_predict_pure[:,0])
test_predict_df = pd.DataFrame(test_predict_pure[:,0])
predict_df = pd.concat([train_predict_df, test_predict_df])
predict_df.reset_index(inplace=True)
predict_df.drop(columns=["index"], inplace=True)

# plot baseline and predictions
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.plot(log_diff_data, color='b', label="original data")
plt.plot(predict_df[:len(train_predict_df)].index + 10, predict_df[:len(train_predict_df)][0], color="g",
         label='training predictions')
plt.plot(predict_df[len(train_predict_df):].index, 
         predict_df[len(train_predict_df):][0], color="r", label="testing predictions")
plt.legend() 
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.show()

data = dataset.values
data = data.astype('float32')
log_data = np.log(data)

first_train_y = log_data[look_back]
# first_test_value = log_data[train_size]

train_predictions = train_predict_pure[:,0]
train_predictions = np.insert(train_predictions, 0, first_train_y)
train_predictions = np.exp(train_predictions.cumsum())

original_train_Y = trainY
original_train_Y = np.insert(original_train_Y, 0, first_train_y)
original_train_Y = np.exp(original_train_Y.cumsum())

trainScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(original_train_Y, train_predictions))
print('Train Score: %.2f RMSE' % (trainScore))

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.plot(original_train_Y, color='g', label='original train y')
plt.plot(train_predictions, color='r', label='predicted train y')
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel("nr. of month")
plt.ylabel("amount of passengers")
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.show()

Train Score: 85.00 RMSE

Strange case when model gave the strangest distribution of predictions, but from RMSE it is not going far from other results. Still, this is the worst case of overfit and going too far from the solution

LSTM four layers, 100 neurons, 100 epoches, log with differential applied¶

In [675]:
data = dataset.values
data = data.astype('float32')
log_data = np.log(data)

log_diff_data = np.diff(log_data, axis=0)

train_size = int(len(log_diff_data) * 0.9167)
test_size = len(log_diff_data) - train_size
train, test = log_diff_data[0:train_size,:], log_diff_data[train_size:len(log_diff_data),:]
print(len(train), len(test))

look_back = 10
trainX, trainY = create_dataset(train, look_back)
testX, testY = create_dataset(test, look_back)

trainX = np.reshape(trainX, (trainX.shape[0], 1, trainX.shape[1]))
testX = np.reshape(testX, (testX.shape[0], 1, testX.shape[1]))

model = Sequential()
# model.add(LSTM(4, input_shape=(1, look_back)))
model.add(LSTM(4, batch_input_shape=(1, 1, look_back), stateful=True, return_sequences=True))
model.add(Dense(100))
model.add(LSTM(4, batch_input_shape=(1, 1, look_back), stateful=True, return_sequences=True))
model.add(Dense(100))
model.add(LSTM(4, batch_input_shape=(1, 1, look_back), stateful=True, return_sequences=True))
model.add(Dense(100))
model.add(LSTM(4, batch_input_shape=(1, 1, look_back), stateful=True))
model.add(Dense(100))
model.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
history = model.fit(trainX, trainY, epochs=100, validation_data=(testX, testY), batch_size=1, verbose=2)

# make predictions
train_predict_pure = model.predict(trainX, batch_size=1)
test_predict_pure = model.predict(testX, batch_size=1)

# calculate root mean squared error
trainScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(trainY, train_predict_pure[:, 0]))
print('Train Score: %.2f RMSE' % (trainScore))
testScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(testY, test_predict_pure[:, 0]))
print('Test Score: %.2f RMSE' % (testScore))

train_predict_df = pd.DataFrame(train_predict_pure[:,0])
test_predict_df = pd.DataFrame(test_predict_pure[:,0])
predict_df = pd.concat([train_predict_df, test_predict_df])
predict_df.reset_index(inplace=True)
predict_df.drop(columns=["index"], inplace=True)

# plot baseline and predictions
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.plot(log_diff_data, color='b', label="original data")
plt.plot(predict_df[:len(train_predict_df)].index + 10, predict_df[:len(train_predict_df)][0], color="g",
         label='training predictions')
plt.plot(predict_df[len(train_predict_df):].index, 
         predict_df[len(train_predict_df):][0], color="r", label="testing predictions")
plt.legend() 
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.show()

data = dataset.values
data = data.astype('float32')
log_data = np.log(data)

first_train_y = log_data[look_back]

train_predictions = train_predict_pure[:,0]
train_predictions = np.insert(train_predictions, 0, first_train_y)
train_predictions = np.exp(train_predictions.cumsum())

original_train_Y = trainY
original_train_Y = np.insert(original_train_Y, 0, first_train_y)
original_train_Y = np.exp(original_train_Y.cumsum())

trainScore = math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(original_train_Y, train_predictions))
print('Train Score: %.2f RMSE' % (trainScore))

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.plot(original_train_Y, color='g', label='original train y')
plt.plot(train_predictions, color='r', label='predicted train y')
plt.legend()
plt.xlabel("nr. of month")
plt.ylabel("amount of passengers")
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--')
plt.show()

Train Score: 85.04 RMSE

The same case as previous model, terrible match with original values

Conclusions¶

Out of all presented models the best matches are in 3 cases:

  1. LSTM over the original data with MinMax scaling and concept of "use current month to predict next one";
  2. LSTM over the data transformed conform laboratory work requirements and with 500 epoches, 25 neurons and one layer;
  3. LSTM over the data transformed conform laboratory work requirements and with 2 layers, 50 neurons per layer, 100 epoches.

The last case will be the most universal one, because it is created with elimination of the cyclic and trending aspects of the original dataset, but closer to the end values start to deviate, meaning that this model should be improved to achieve better results and make sure that it can be used in the future.

The second case also gives great result, which starts to differ more and more going further through time. It also will require more improvements to be usable with more records.

The first model looks very promising. It is primitive, but efficient concept that led to great results and the best RMSE results.
